[[File:Flickr_-_ggallice_-_Swamp_in_Osceola_National_Forest.jpg|thumb|Forested swamp in [[Osceola National Forest]]]] '''Palustrine wetlands''' include any inland [[wetland]] that lacks flowing water, contains ocean-derived salts in concentrations of less than 0.5 [[parts per thousand]], and is non-[[tide|tidal]].<ref name=Cowardin>{{cite web|last1=Cowardin|first1=L. M.|last2=Carter|first2=V.|last3=Golet|first3=F. C.|last4=LaRoe|first4=E. T.|title=Classification of wetlands and deepwater habitats of the United States|url=https://www.fws.gov/wetlands/Documents/classwet/index.html|publisher=U.S. Department of the Interior, Fish and Wildlife Service|accessdate=26 April 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140121073314/http://www.fws.gov/wetlands/Documents/classwet/index.html|archivedate=21 January 2014|format=HTML}}</ref> The word ''palustrine'' comes from the [[Latin]] word ''palus'' or [[marsh]].<ref>{{cite web|title=American Heritage® Dictionary of the English Language, Fifth Edition.|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/palustrine|website=The Free Dictionary|accessdate=26 April 2015}}</ref> Wetlands within this category include inland [[marsh]]es and [[swamp]]s as well as [[bog]]s, [[fen]]s, [[tundra]] and [[floodplain]]s.
Palustrine wetlands are one of five categories of wetlands within the [[Cowardin classification system]]. The other categories are:<ref name=Cowardin /> * [[Marine (ocean)|Marine]] wetlands, exposed to the open ocean * [[Estuarine]] wetlands, partially enclosed by land and containing a mix of fresh and salt water * [[Riverine]] wetlands, associated with flowing water * Lacustrine wetlands, associated with a [[lake]] or other body of fresh water
